Churn Modelling

  1. Data Preparation and Analysis
  2. Model Evaluation and Selection
  3. Feature Importance and Reduction

Goal: Build a reproducible machine learning model that can predict bank churn.

Dataset Source: https://www.kaggle.com/shrutimechlearn/churn-modelling

Project Repository: https://github.com/jaredible/CS4300-Project

Data Splitting¶

Data Randomization¶

By shuffling the data, we ensure that each data point creates an independent change on the model without being biased by the same ones before them.

Data Normalization¶

Normalization aims to change numeric columns' values in the dataset to a standard scale without distorting differences in value ranges.

Pre-Normalization¶

In [42]:
# Visualize input distribution before normalization
dfx = pd.DataFrame(data = TX)
dfx.columns = rdf.drop('exited', axis = 'columns').columns
hist = dfx.hist(figsize = (13, 20), grid = True, bins = 10, color = '#686de0', alpha = 0.9)

Normalization¶

In [43]:
# Mean normalization
min = TX.min(axis = 0)
max = TX.max(axis = 0)
mean = TX.mean(axis = 0)
XTRAIN = (TX - mean) / (max - min)
XVALID = (VX - mean) / (max - min)

# Observe details
print(XTRAIN.shape)
print(XTRAIN)
print(XVALID.shape)

Model Evaluation and Selection¶

The goal here is to evaluate multiple models and select the best one that overfits the data. Developing a model, in general, typically has several main steps:

  1. Creation (constructing the model)
  2. Visualization (showing how the neurons in the model are connected)
  3. Compilation (assigning optimization and loss functions for the model)
  4. Training (adjusting the weights and biases in the model)
  5. Evaluation (checking how well the model correctly classifies the data)
In [ ]:
EPOCHS = 2 ** 10
BATCH_SIZE = 2 ** 5

def model_compile(model, optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['acc']):
  model.compile(optimizer = optimizer, loss = loss, metrics = metrics)

Model Training¶

The goal of training a model is to find a set of weights and biases that have low loss, on average, across all the data.

In [ ]:
def model_train(model, train_data = (XTRAIN, YTRAIN), valid_data = (XVALID, YVALID), epochs = EPOCHS, batch_size = BATCH_SIZE, verbose = 1):
  K.clear_session()

  callbacks = []
  callbacks.append(ModelCheckpoint(filepath = f"{log_dir}/{model.name}.h5", monitor = 'val_loss', save_best_only = True, save_weights_only = True, verbose = verbose))
  callbacks.append(EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 30, verbose = verbose))

  start = time.time()
  history = model.fit(train_data[0], train_data[1], validation_data = (valid_data[0], valid_data[1]), epochs = epochs, batch_size = batch_size, verbose = verbose, callbacks = callbacks)
  end = time.time()

  return (history, end - start)

Model Evaluation¶

Evaluation helps to find the best model that represents our data and how well the chosen model will work in the future.

In [ ]:
def model_evaluate(model, history, train_data = (XTRAIN, YTRAIN), valid_data = (XVALID, YVALID), accuracy_metrics = ('acc', 'val_acc'), loss_metrics = ('loss', 'val_loss'), legend_location = 0b0000):
  # Show model accuracy and loss metrics
  scores = model.evaluate(valid_data[0], valid_data[1])

  # Get model predictions
  prediction = model.predict(valid_data[0]) > 0.5

  # Show model statistics
  accuracy = accuracy_score(valid_data[1], prediction.round()) * 100.0
  precision = precision_score(valid_data[1], prediction.round(), zero_division = 0) * 100.0
  recall = recall_score(valid_data[1], prediction.round(), zero_division = 0) * 100.0
  f1 = f1_score(valid_data[1], prediction.round(), zero_division = 0) * 100.0
  print(f"Accuracy:  {accuracy:.2f}%")
  print(f"Precision: {precision:.2f}%")
  print(f"Recall:    {recall:.2f}%")
  print(f"F1:        {f1:.2f}%")

  # Show classification correctness
  incorrectly_classified = np.count_nonzero(YVALID.astype(int) != 1 * prediction[:, 0])
  correctly_classified = len(YVALID) - incorrectly_classified
  print(f"# of correctly classified:   {correctly_classified}")
  print(f"# of incorrectly classified: {incorrectly_classified}")

  fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize = (12, 4))

  xlocs = ['left', 'right']
  ylocs = ['lower', 'upper']

  # Plot train and validation accuracy
  ax1.plot(history.history[accuracy_metrics[0]])
  ax1.plot(history.history[accuracy_metrics[1]])
  ax1.set(title = f"Model '{model.name}' Accuracy", xlabel = 'Epoch', ylabel = 'Accuracy')
  ax1.legend(['Training data', 'Validation data'], loc = f"{ylocs[1 * bool(legend_location & (1 << (2)))]} {xlocs[1 * bool(legend_location & (1 << (3)))]}")

  # Plot train and validation loss
  ax2.plot(history.history[loss_metrics[0]])
  ax2.plot(history.history[loss_metrics[1]])
  ax2.set(title = f"Model '{model.name}' Loss", xlabel = 'Epoch', ylabel = 'Loss')
  ax2.legend(['Training data', 'Validation data'], loc = f"{ylocs[1 * bool(legend_location & (1 << (0)))]} {xlocs[1 * bool(legend_location & (1 << (1)))]}")

  # Plot actual versus predicted results
  cm = confusion_matrix(valid_data[1], prediction)
  ax = sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, annot_kws = {'size': 15}, xticklabels = ['No', 'Yes'], yticklabels = ['No', 'Yes'], linewidths = 2, fmt = 'g')
  ax.invert_yaxis()
  ax3.set_xlabel("Predicted")
  ax3.set_ylabel("Actual")

  fig.tight_layout()
  fig.show()

  return (accuracy, precision, recall, f1, correctly_classified, incorrectly_classified)

Feature Importance and Reduction¶

Feature Importance¶

In [ ]:
feature_importance_accuracies = {}
feature_importance_histories = {}

for column in rdf.drop('exited', axis = 'columns'): #for index in range(dataset.shape[1] - 1):
  print(column)
  x = rdf[column].values
  y = rdf['exited'].values

  # Index for 20%
  index = int(0.2 * len(dataset[:, 0]))

  # Split into training (80%) set
  tx = x[index:]
  ty = y[index:]
  # Split into validation (20%) set
  vx = x[:index]
  vy = y[:index]

  # Mean normalization
  min = tx.min(axis = 0)
  max = tx.max(axis = 0)
  mean = tx.mean(axis = 0)
  tx = (tx - mean) / (max - min)
  vx = (vx - mean) / (max - min)

  # Rescaling
  ym = ty.max()
  ty = ty / ym
  vy = vy / ym

  K.clear_session()

  callbacks = []
  callbacks.append(ModelCheckpoint(filepath = f"feature_importance_{column}.h5", monitor = 'val_loss', save_best_only = True, save_weights_only = True, verbose = 1))
  callbacks.append(EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 30, verbose = 1))

  model = Sequential(name=f"feature_importance_{column}")
  model.add(Dense(130, activation = 'relu', input_dim = 1))
  model.add(Dense(65, activation = 'relu'))
  model.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))
  model.summary()

  model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['acc'])
  history = model.fit(tx, ty, validation_data = (vx, vy), epochs = 1024, batch_size = 32, callbacks = callbacks)
  feature_importance_histories[column] = history

  pred = model.predict(vx) > 0.5
  acc = accuracy_score(vy, pred)
  feature_importance_accuracies[column] = acc
  print(acc)

Feature Reduction¶

Starting with all features and removing the least significant iteratively.

In [ ]:
tdf = rdf.drop('exited', axis = 'columns')
feature_reduction_accuracies = {}
feature_reduction_histories = {}

# TODO: automate
sorted_feature_importance_accuracies = [
        'product_count',
        'age',
        'credit_score',
        'balance',
        'tenure',
        'has_credit_card',
        'active',
        'estimated_salary',
        'geography__france',
        'geography__germany',
        'geography__spain',
        'gender__female',
        'gender__male'
        ]

for column in sorted_feature_importance_accuracies[::-1]:
  print(column)
  x = tdf.values
  y = rdf['exited'].values

  # Index for 20%
  index = int(0.2 * len(dataset[:, 0]))

  # Split into training (80%) set
  tx = x[index:]
  ty = y[index:]
  # Split into validation (20%) set
  vx = x[:index]
  vy = y[:index]

  print(tx.shape)

  # Mean normalization
  min = tx.min(axis = 0)
  max = tx.max(axis = 0)
  mean = tx.mean(axis = 0)
  tx = (tx - mean) / (max - min)
  vx = (vx - mean) / (max - min)

  # Rescaling
  ym = ty.max()
  ty = ty / ym
  vy = vy / ym

  K.clear_session()

  callbacks = []
  callbacks.append(ModelCheckpoint(filepath = f"feature_reduction_{column}.h5", monitor = 'val_loss', save_best_only = True, save_weights_only = True, verbose = 1))
  callbacks.append(EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 30, verbose = 1))

  model = Sequential(name=f"feature_reduction_{column}")
  model.add(Dense(13, activation = tf.nn.leaky_relu, input_dim = len(tx[0, :])))
  model.add(Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(Dense(26, activation = tf.nn.leaky_relu))
  model.add(Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(Dense(13, activation = tf.nn.leaky_relu))
  model.add(Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))
  model.summary()

  model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['acc'])
  history = model.fit(tx, ty, validation_data = (vx, vy), epochs = 1024, batch_size = 32, callbacks = callbacks)
  feature_reduction_histories[column] = history

  pred = model.predict(vx) > 0.5
  acc = accuracy_score(vy, pred)
  feature_reduction_accuracies[column] = acc
  print(acc)

  tdf = tdf.drop(column, axis = 'columns')

margin = 0.01
h = np.arange(len(feature_reduction_accuracies.keys()))
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10, 10))
plt.title('Feature Reduction Accuracies')
bars = ax.bar(h, feature_reduction_accuracies.values(), align = 'center', alpha = 0.5)
plt.xticks(h, feature_reduction_accuracies.keys(), fontsize = 10, rotation = 90)
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.ylim(np.maximum(np.amin(list(feature_reduction_accuracies.values())) - margin, 0.0), np.minimum(np.amax(list(feature_reduction_accuracies.values())) + margin, 1.0))
for rec in bars.patches:
  ax.annotate(format(rec.get_height(), '.4f'), (rec.get_x() + rec.get_width() / 2.0, rec.get_height()), ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 5), textcoords = 'offset points', fontsize = 10)
plt.show()
